  				<span><span class="alias">Comer en BCN</span></span>
  				<span>on September 29, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2847"><p>geez, i&#8217;ve got a lot to say.  quick, the best: when we left the big cities, we had some really, really fun sunday dinners in way out of the way country restaurants.  like, in places where people went with their parents and kids and the meals had lots of courses.  i remember one really formal one with pate and squab and stuff.  and one really informal one with roasted meat and crisp vegetables. we had a car but returned it once we arrived in barcelona.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">zp</span></span>
  				<span>on September 29, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2848"><p>Comer, I looked at the website for the restaurant group you mentioned and they do look fabulous! Maybe for a special dinner&#8230;</p>
<p>zp, what you are saying makes sense, do you have any more details?</p>
<p>Thanks, Gerda!</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca</span></span>
  				<span>on September 29, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2849"><p>Actually, those two Sunday dinners weren&#8217;t near Barcelona.  But I thought I&#8217;d just throw the idea out there, in case you wanted to try to find something similiar, wherever you might find yourself, on a Sunday afternoon. In Barcelona I remember a place with snails and grilled meats on the edge of the very ritzy part of town and the restaurant&#8217;s sign had a bright blue snail . . . Dark and quiet and reasonable and tasty.   That&#8217;s as much as I can remember five years hence.</p></div>
